message.content:
A 'Tringa solitaria' is a small wading bird of the sandpiper family.
It has brownish-gray feathers on its upper body and white feathers on its underparts.
The bill is straight and slender, measuring about two inches long.
It has long, yellowish-green legs and webbed feet adapted for wading and swimming.
The wings are pointed and extend slightly beyond the tail in flight.
It is typically found in wetland habitats such as marshes, mudflats, and coastal estuaries.
During migration, it can be found along the coasts of North and South America.
